.START 

Citing a write-off, WordStar International Inc. said it posted a net loss for its fourth quarter ended Aug. 31. 

The San Rafael, Calif., software concern said it posted a loss of $793,000, or six cents a share.
The loss included a $1 million write-off for its investment in a product acquired from Challenger Software of Homewood, Ill. 

WordStar had a loss of $1.1 million, or eight cents a share, a year ago.
Revenue fell 6.6% to $11.3 million from $12.1 million. 

For the year, WordStar had a loss of $3 million, or 22 cents a share, compared with a loss of $5.1 million, or 38 cents a share, a year earlier.
Revenue rose 1.6% to $43.2 million from $42.5 million. 

Separately, Kevin Smith, vice president and chief financial officer resigned.
Gari Grimm, WordStar president and chief executive officer, said Mr. Smith's contract was up for renewal and "we were unable to reach agreement on the terms of his new contract." Jim Dalrymple, vice president of strategic planning, will assume Mr. Smith's duties until a permanent replacement is found. 

